{#- VARIANT DETAIL (definition) — plain-terms prose body -#}
<section class="sec reveal" id="checklist-sales-tax-definition" style="padding-top:24px;">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="eyebrow" style="margin-bottom:8px;">In plain terms</div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:18px;">Sales tax compliance, plainly.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>Sales tax compliance means charging the right tax to the right customers in the right states, then filing and remitting it on time &mdash; and being able to prove all of it on audit. It starts with <strong>nexus</strong>: the connection to a state that creates an obligation to collect its sales tax. Nexus is either <em>physical</em> (an office, employees, inventory, or property in the state) or <em>economic</em> (crossing the state&rsquo;s sales or transaction threshold). Once you know which states you&rsquo;re in, the rest follows in order &mdash; register, configure rates in QuickBooks, collect on taxable sales, keep exemption certificates, file and remit, and reconcile.</p>
      <p>The good news is that the operational side is a defined, repeatable system &mdash; the checklist below &mdash; and QuickBooks&rsquo; automated sales-tax engine does a lot of the rate math once it&rsquo;s configured. What the checklist <em>doesn&rsquo;t</em> do is make a legal call on where you owe. Determining nexus across multiple states is a tax-law judgment that carries liability, so it belongs with a CPA, EA, or sales-tax specialist. We keep the books and the collection right and coordinate with your professional on the determinations and the filings &mdash; we don&rsquo;t give legal or tax advice.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

